  |text='''[[Mikhail_Baryshnikov|Mikhail Nikolaevitch Baryshnikov]]''' ({{lang-ru|Михаил Николаевич Барышников}}) (born January 28, 1948) is a famous [[Russia|Russia]]n [[dancer|dancer]], [[choreographer|choreographer]], and [[actor|actor]].

Baryshnikov, whose name is sometimes [[transliteration|transliterated]] as ''Baryshinikov'' or ''Barishinikov'', was born in [[Riga|Riga]], [[Latvia|Latvia]] to Russian parents. His mother enrolled him in the School of Theatre Opera Ballet in Riga when he was twelve. In time, he decided to follow a career as a dancer. 

Baryshnikov was a unique dancer in many ways. He was short and thus had to work hard to prove his suitability for roles such as Siegfried in [[Swan_Lake|Swan Lake]] where a taller, more noble bearing was expected. His dancing was renowned for its textbook form, technical brilliance, and emotional detachment.
